Therefore, the high antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory activities of the LCP (
 Tarasova et al., 1998; 
 Semkina et al., 2006; 
 Vichkanova, 2012) may be associated with the presence of macrocarpals A and B and ursane type triterpenoids. However, composition of the LCP metabolites and their known properties suggest that the range of pharmacological activities of the LCP may be much wider than previously shown.
